[1] Kazakhstan: Chinese Embassy issues alert re pneumonia, RFI
[A]
Date: Thu 9 Jul 2020
Source: Chinese Embassy in Kazakhstan [in Chinese, trans. Rapp.DS, edited]
http://kz.chineseembassy.org/chn/sgxx/sgdt/t1796496.htm


Alerting Chinese citizens in Kazakhstan to take precautions against unknown pneumonia:
According to Kazakhstan media reports, the incidence of pneumonia in Atyrau Region, Aktobe, and Shymkent has significantly increased since mid-June 2020, [compared to] the same period [in 2019]. Up to today [9 Jul 2020], the 3 regions have had nearly 500 infections and more than 30 people are critically ill. In the 1st half of this year [2020], 1772 people died of pneumonia in Kazakhstan. In June [2020] alone, there were already 628 deaths, among which were Chinese citizens. The fatality rate of this illness is far higher than COVID-19. The Kazakhstan Ministry of Health and other agencies are now carrying out research on this pneumonia virus but do not yet have a definitive determination. China's embassy to Kazakhstan warns Chinese citizens in Kazakhstan to be mindful of this situation and pay increased attention to prevention to lower the risk of infection.

1. Pay close attention to information from the Kazakh government and Chinese embassy in Kazakhstan. Do not create, believe, or spread rumors.
2. Take protective measures and minimize outings, avoiding crowded areas. Pay attention to personal protection and hand hygiene, maintaining good hygiene and health habits. Wear masks when going out, wash hands frequently, disinfect frequently, and maintain ventilation.
3. If you develop symptoms, seek medical attention in a timely manner and inform your physician of your travel and contact history, actively supporting related investigations.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Dan Silver

----
[B]
Date: Thu 9 Jul 2020 10:51 PM CST
Source: South China Morning Post [abridged, edited]
https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3092563/chinese-embassy-warns-deadly-unknown-pneumonia-kazakhstan


The Chinese embassy in Kazakhstan has warned of a deadly "unknown pneumonia" after the former Soviet republic reported a spike in pneumonia cases since June [2020]. While the Chinese embassy described the illness as an "unknown pneumonia", Kazakhstani officials and media have only said it is pneumonia. It was not clear why the Chinese embassy had described the illness as "unknown" or what information it had about the pneumonia. The embassy's website, citing local media reports, said the provinces of Atyrau and Aktobe and the city of Shymkent have reported significant spikes in pneumonia cases since the middle of June [2020].

Shymkent and the capital city of Atyrau are 1500 km (930 miles) apart, while the distance between the capital cities of Atyrau and Aktobe is 330 km (205 miles). Saule Kisikova, the health care department chief in the capital Nur-Sultan, told the news agency Kazinform: "Some 300 people diagnosed with pneumonia are being hospitalised every day." The agency also said there had been 1700 pneumonia cases nationwide in June [2020] -- more than 2 times the number in the same month last year [2019].

Kazakhstan announced a state of emergency on [6 Mar 2020] to tackle the spread of COVID-19. The lockdown was lifted on [11 May 2020], but restrictions and quarantine measures have been reimposed in some areas following the surge in pneumonia cases. Kazakhstan's President Kassym-Jomart Tokayev said in a televised address on Wednesday [8 Jul 2020] that the situation was still serious and it was too early to relax restrictions. He added the country was "in fact facing the 2nd coronavirus wave coupled with a huge uptick in pneumonia cases", according to the Russian news agency Tass.

Late last month [Jun 2020] officials warned about the rise in pneumonia cases. Kisikova said that doctors were finding 600 people a day with pneumonia symptoms, compared with 80 a day before the start of the Covid-19 outbreak, the Singapore-based website CNA reported. "Every day, 350 to 400 patients are hospitalised in the city with either Covid-19 or pneumonia," she said.

[Byline: Wendy Wu]

--
Communicated by:
Ryan McGinnis
<ryan@digicana.com>

