Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In the past 24 hours, according to the report at the source URL, the tally of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in South Korea has increased by 45 cases with 1 new death, compared with 50 cases and 2 new deaths in the previous day (8 Jul 2020). The daily newly confirmed case count has been at or below 100 for 87 consecutive days. There were 22 locally transmitted cases: Seoul (7), Daejeon (7), Gwangju (3), Gyeonggi (3), and Jeonnam (2), and 23 imported cases -- Gyeonggi (11), airport quarantine (4), Gyeongnam (3), Chungbuk (2), Seoul (1), Incheon (1), and Jeonnam (1). There were 9 provinces reporting no newly confirmed cases (compared with 6 provinces yesterday, 8 Jul 2020).

According to data from the "ncov" website of the Ministry of Health and Welfare, the cumulative confirmation rate has been steady at 1.0% (http://ncov.mohw.go.kr/). The English language pages for notices 423 and 424 provide details on the 50 cases confirmed yesterday 8 Jul 2020 and updates on active clusters. (https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=&bid=0030).

The overall impression hasn't changed: lifting of measures has been accompanied by increases in locally acquired infections through increasing clusters related to gatherings of people at employment (bringing it outside employment to contacts) and in houses of worship, and bars and clubs. But, that being said, importations are also playing a major role in the country. It would be nice to know the asymptomatic rate being detected, and the proportion of asymptomatic infections detected that go on to clinical disease.

A map of South Korea showing provinces can be seen at https://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/korea-south-administrative-map.htm and a HealthMap/ProMED map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7560034,195. - Mod.MPP]

